WEBVTT

00:12.303 --> 00:14.305
<i>- One thing</i>
<i>you come to understand</i>

00:14.347 --> 00:16.391
<i>about Northern Minnesota,</i>

00:16.433 --> 00:19.686
<i>from Lake Superior</i>
<i>to the Iron Range,</i>

00:19.728 --> 00:23.356
<i>water and ice have shaped</i>
<i>this land and its people</i>

00:23.398 --> 00:25.233
<i>for generations.</i>

00:25.275 --> 00:28.028
<i>Now, as for that Iron Range,</i>

00:28.069 --> 00:30.196
<i>it's an area filled with--</i>

00:30.238 --> 00:33.867
<i>well, I guess we spoiled it--</i>
<i>iron.</i>

00:33.908 --> 00:35.869
<i>Which is code for mining.</i>

00:35.910 --> 00:38.371
<i>It was originally settled</i>
<i>by the Scots,</i>

00:38.413 --> 00:42.000
<i>who instilled a few hallmarks</i>
<i>that still define life here--</i>

00:42.042 --> 00:44.836
<i>a tough, gritty work ethic</i>

00:44.878 --> 00:48.173
<i>and a game called curling.</i>

00:48.214 --> 00:51.801
<i>To this day, that's what</i>
<i>people do in the Iron Range.</i>

00:51.843 --> 00:54.971
<i>They work in mines,</i>
<i>and they curl.</i>

00:55.013 --> 00:59.100
<i>Meaning it's no surprise</i>
<i>that a town like Chisholm</i>

00:59.142 --> 01:00.977
<i>produced the best curler</i>

01:01.019 --> 01:04.647
<i>the United States of America</i>
<i>has ever seen.</i>

01:06.900 --> 01:11.321
<i>- Curling Club was built here</i>
<i>in Chisholm in about 1960.</i>

01:11.363 --> 01:15.492
I started curling with my dad
here in about 1967.

01:15.992 --> 01:19.162
<i>Curling, it's something</i>
<i>that gets handed down</i>

01:19.204 --> 01:22.040
<i>from generation</i>
<i>to generation, and, uh,</i>

01:22.082 --> 01:25.710
<i>there's a tradition</i>
<i>of good curlers in Chisholm.</i>

01:26.544 --> 01:28.630
<i>And that is it.</i>

01:28.672 --> 01:32.842
<i>The United States has won</i>
<i>curling gold at the Olympics.</i>

01:35.845 --> 01:38.473
<i>- There's a lot of pride</i>
<i>with John being from Chisholm</i>

01:38.515 --> 01:41.643
and his roots doing curling
being from Chisholm.

01:41.685 --> 01:44.938
<i>- John Shuster</i>
<i>is Chisholm's prodigal son,</i>

01:44.979 --> 01:48.775
<i>the hometown boy who struck</i>
<i>gold in South Korea</i>

01:48.817 --> 01:51.528
<i>and proudly</i>
<i>brought it back home...</i>

01:51.569 --> 01:55.240
<i>though the excitement</i>
<i>over the 2018 Olympic win</i>

01:55.281 --> 01:59.327
<i>for Shuster's team spread</i>
<i>far beyond Northern Minnesota.</i>

01:59.369 --> 02:00.745
<i>2018...</i>

02:00.787 --> 02:02.914
<i>- And they soaked up</i>
<i>the moment</i>

02:02.956 --> 02:05.083
<i>on their nationwide</i>
<i>victory lap.</i>

02:05.125 --> 02:06.668
<i>Let's do this, fellas!</i>

02:06.710 --> 02:09.004
<i>- It would not</i>
<i>surprise me a bit</i>

02:09.045 --> 02:11.131
<i>if they were to go</i>
<i>to another Olympics.</i>

02:11.172 --> 02:12.674
- The gold medal winning
curling team.

02:12.716 --> 02:14.384
Hey, guys.

02:14.426 --> 02:15.927
<i>- Chisholm's gonna be</i>
<i>watching John real close</i>

02:15.969 --> 02:17.679
<i>on this next one</i>
<i>and rooting for him,</i>

02:17.721 --> 02:20.557
and I'll be following
every game closely.

02:21.433 --> 02:24.060
<i>- John and the boys enjoyed</i>
<i>every bit</i>

02:24.102 --> 02:25.979
<i>of their flash of fame.</i>

02:26.021 --> 02:27.522
<i>But when it was all over,</i>

02:27.564 --> 02:30.150
<i>there was only</i>
<i>one place to go:</i>

02:30.191 --> 02:33.111
<i>back home to the Iron Range</i>

02:33.153 --> 02:36.322
<i>where the next goal</i>
<i>quickly came into focus:</i>

02:36.364 --> 02:38.533
<i>becoming the first</i>
<i>curling team ever</i>

02:38.575 --> 02:41.703
<i>to win back-to-back</i>
<i>Olympic gold.</i>

02:41.745 --> 02:44.456
<i>If it sounds improbable,</i>
<i>remember,</i>

02:44.497 --> 02:48.335
<i>they already</i>
<i>accomplished the impossible.</i>

03:14.152 --> 03:15.695
<i>We'll pick up our story</i>

03:15.737 --> 03:18.573
<i>a little more than three years</i>
<i>after PyeongChang</i>

03:18.615 --> 03:21.743
<i>and four months before</i>
<i>the next Olympic trials.</i>

03:21.785 --> 03:23.995
<i>For Team Shuster,</i>
<i>the clock is ticking,</i>

03:24.037 --> 03:26.915
<i>which means</i>
<i>the gym is beckoning.</i>

03:26.956 --> 03:30.126
<i>What, you didn't</i>
<i>think curlers cross-trained?</i>

03:30.168 --> 03:32.128
<i>Of course you didn't.</i>

03:32.170 --> 03:36.007
<i>Though the workouts actually</i>
<i>range from state-of-the-art</i>

03:36.049 --> 03:38.093
<i>to the old classics.</i>

03:38.134 --> 03:39.594
You're right here.

03:39.636 --> 03:42.389
- We have push-ups first.
Great.

03:42.430 --> 03:44.391
This is way too early
to be working out.

03:44.432 --> 03:47.477
- Is this 60 or 30?
- 60 seconds.

03:47.519 --> 03:49.938
- You can stop filming me
after 30 seconds.

03:49.979 --> 03:52.273
- We edit these tight,
boys, real tight.

03:52.315 --> 03:54.943
Give 'em two push-ups, and be
like, yeah, he's pretty fit.

03:54.984 --> 03:56.778
Set, go.

03:56.820 --> 03:59.906
Three, four--all the way down,
five, six--

03:59.948 --> 04:02.617
- Take your time.
Plenty of time.

04:02.659 --> 04:04.452
<i>- You take a look</i>
<i>at our team compared to</i>

04:04.494 --> 04:05.745
<i>these younger teams,</i>

04:05.787 --> 04:08.748
we're obviously
not as physically fit.

04:08.790 --> 04:10.333
- Come on, Landst.

04:10.375 --> 04:11.418
- You got it, buddy,
you got it.

04:11.459 --> 04:12.627
27.

04:12.669 --> 04:14.295
<i>I shouldn't even say this.</i>

04:14.337 --> 04:16.756
I think that I'm a nat--

04:16.798 --> 04:18.717
like a born-natural athlete.

04:20.010 --> 04:23.346
27, 8...

04:23.388 --> 04:24.973
28.

04:25.015 --> 04:26.725
Good.
Done!

04:26.766 --> 04:29.811
- Testing for me and testing
for my teammates, I think,

04:29.853 --> 04:32.647
I have a much different,
like, mindset toward it,

04:32.689 --> 04:35.025
where I kind of, like,
enjoy seeing what I can do.

04:35.066 --> 04:36.317
- 27...

04:36.359 --> 04:37.652
- Got to catch me.
- 28.

04:37.694 --> 04:39.154
- Yeah!

04:39.195 --> 04:40.155
- Yeah.
- Jeez.

04:40.196 --> 04:41.406
Whoo!

04:41.448 --> 04:43.324
Brutal.

04:43.366 --> 04:44.701
<i>I think some of my teammates--</i>

04:44.743 --> 04:46.119
<i>I don't think they get</i>
<i>the enjoyment out of it</i>

04:46.161 --> 04:48.496
<i>because they are</i>
<i>giving it their all,</i>

04:48.538 --> 04:50.373
<i>and it's not enjoyable.</i>

04:50.415 --> 04:54.544
- I--I hate
the physical testing.

04:54.586 --> 04:58.757
- Five, four, three,

04:58.798 --> 05:00.342
two, one.

05:00.383 --> 05:03.136
- 27, man.
- I had 48.

05:03.178 --> 05:04.929
I did not.

05:08.099 --> 05:12.896
<i>- In the gym, they embody</i>
<i>a range of profiles.</i>

05:12.937 --> 05:15.940
<i>And the same goes for their</i>
<i>personalities as well.</i>

05:17.817 --> 05:19.402
<i>- We have a very good balance</i>
<i>on our team,</i>

05:19.444 --> 05:21.696
<i>and it works very well.</i>

05:21.738 --> 05:24.824
My role is the quiet guy
slash introvert

05:24.866 --> 05:30.288
that kind of brings down the--
the energy in a good way.

05:30.330 --> 05:32.916
- You look really excited,
Steiner.

05:32.957 --> 05:35.210
I'm up.

05:35.251 --> 05:36.711
Attaboy, Shu!

05:36.753 --> 05:38.296
<i>- Matty's definitely</i>
<i>got a personality.</i>

05:38.338 --> 05:40.507
<i>Like, it doesn't really matter</i>
<i>what kind of</i>

05:40.548 --> 05:42.258
<i>circumstances we're in.</i>

05:42.300 --> 05:43.802
- Attaboy.
Good job.

05:45.136 --> 05:47.013
- Matt's a good teammate, man.
He, uh...

05:47.055 --> 05:50.558
he's just kind of our guy for--
for the energy.

05:50.600 --> 05:52.185
- What are you doing?
Pull-ups?

05:52.227 --> 05:54.562
- Yeah.

05:56.314 --> 05:57.899
<i>- Chris, Chris is, uh--</i>

05:57.941 --> 06:00.068
calm, cool, and collected,
I would say.

06:00.110 --> 06:01.945
Man.

06:01.986 --> 06:05.323
<i>- Lotta people, uh,</i>
<i>know our team to be the--</i>

06:05.365 --> 06:08.410
<i>the gold medal team,</i>
<i>so we have a fresh guy,</i>

06:08.451 --> 06:10.829
and it's working out awesome.

06:14.249 --> 06:17.002
No wonder you can throw
a 4-1/2-second peel.

06:17.043 --> 06:18.920
My God!

06:18.962 --> 06:21.673
If you guys want to see
the worst vertical jumper

06:21.715 --> 06:23.425
in elite athlete history,

06:23.466 --> 06:25.176
you're looking
at him right now.

06:26.553 --> 06:27.762
Hey!

06:27.804 --> 06:29.597
John's just one of the, like,

06:29.639 --> 06:32.517
most ultra-competitive
dudes I've met.

06:33.685 --> 06:35.603
-
<i>- John's a gamer.</i>

06:35.645 --> 06:37.939
He's had the same
hunger...

06:37.981 --> 06:40.316
the entire time
I played with him.

06:42.152 --> 06:43.820
Got a lot to do, boys.

06:43.862 --> 06:45.697
Doesn't matter
about your score is.

06:45.739 --> 06:47.240
We win on the ice.

06:57.208 --> 06:59.127
<i>- You do know</i>
<i>that John Shuster</i>

06:59.169 --> 07:02.255
<i>isn't Chisholm's only</i>
<i>sporting legend, right?</i>

07:02.297 --> 07:04.007
<i>Because way back when,</i>

07:04.049 --> 07:06.009
<i>a baseball player</i>
<i>from the town</i>

07:06.051 --> 07:09.804
<i>famously reached the major</i>
<i>leagues for just one game.</i>

07:09.846 --> 07:12.307
<i>His name was Moonlight Graham.</i>

07:12.349 --> 07:15.185
<i>Shuster has lasted longer</i>
<i>on the ice</i>

07:15.226 --> 07:17.020
<i>than Graham did</i>
<i>on the diamond.</i>

07:17.062 --> 07:19.481
<i>But nearly a century apart,</i>

07:19.522 --> 07:22.150
<i>the stories of the two boys</i>
<i>from Chisholm</i>

07:22.192 --> 07:25.487
<i>each are tales</i>
<i>that epitomize the idea</i>

07:25.528 --> 07:28.865
<i>that hard work</i>
<i>has its rewards.</i>

07:28.907 --> 07:30.533
- All right, let's see it.
- Kick it!

07:30.575 --> 07:32.535
- Oh!
Save goalie.

07:32.577 --> 07:33.620
- Avery!
- Yeah.

07:33.661 --> 07:35.580
- Left-footed.

07:35.622 --> 07:37.624
Goal!

07:39.084 --> 07:41.294
Usually, I pull the shirt up
over my head and run around,

07:41.336 --> 07:44.964
but today I'm not feeling
quite so brave.

07:45.006 --> 07:49.052
<i>- Olympic superstar?</i>
<i>In the eyes of some, maybe.</i>

07:49.094 --> 07:52.806
<i>But this is Shuster</i>
<i>in his true natural habitat,</i>

07:52.847 --> 07:54.891
<i>with his family,</i>

07:54.933 --> 07:56.851
<i>a place where balance</i>
<i>and normalcy</i>

07:56.893 --> 07:59.229
<i>define a simpler life.</i>

07:59.270 --> 08:02.482
<i>And where, on this day,</i>
<i>sons Luke and Logan</i>

08:02.524 --> 08:05.694
<i>become just the latest</i>
<i>John Shuster opponents</i>

08:05.735 --> 08:07.237
<i>to meet defeat.</i>

08:07.278 --> 08:09.155
One time!

08:09.197 --> 08:12.033
<i>Life changed following</i>
<i>the 2018 games,</i>

08:12.075 --> 08:15.245
or yeah, I mean,
okay, superstar status.

08:15.286 --> 08:16.329
Good luck stopping Logan.

08:16.371 --> 08:17.455
<i>I think my kids now are--</i>

08:17.497 --> 08:19.416
<i>are getting old enough where--</i>

08:19.457 --> 08:21.584
where they realize how--

08:21.626 --> 08:22.752
how cool it is.

08:22.794 --> 08:24.379
Sorry, Logan, I tried.

08:24.421 --> 08:25.797
<i>You know, maybe they'll be</i>
<i>following in my footsteps</i>

08:25.839 --> 08:26.965
<i>and be doing</i>
<i>something similar,</i>

08:27.007 --> 08:29.801
but they have big dreams
ahead of them too.

08:32.429 --> 08:33.972
<i>I knew what curling was</i>

08:34.014 --> 08:35.640
<i>from probably</i>
<i>the time I could walk,</i>

08:35.682 --> 08:39.310
<i>'cause that was a sport</i>
<i>that my dad chose to play.</i>

08:39.352 --> 08:42.105
Lot of people, to pass,
you know, winters or whatever,

08:42.147 --> 08:44.024
you know, joined bowling
leagues or softball leagues,

08:44.065 --> 08:46.192
that kind of thing and, um,
and my dad happened

08:46.234 --> 08:49.320
to go and start playing
in curling leagues.

08:50.155 --> 08:51.865
<i>I always wanted to try</i>
<i>throwing a curling rock</i>

08:51.906 --> 08:53.950
<i>like my dad and his</i>
<i>friends did and, um,</i>

08:53.992 --> 08:55.744
<i>yeah, and I went</i>
<i>and tried it</i>

08:55.785 --> 08:59.247
<i>in March of my sixth grade</i>
<i>year of--of middle school,</i>

08:59.289 --> 09:02.208
and, uh, slid up on my toe
in this tuck slide,

09:02.250 --> 09:06.838
and slid a rock
down the ice and, um,

09:06.880 --> 09:08.298
you know, probably the fifth
or sixth time,

09:08.340 --> 09:10.008
I, you know,
hit the house and--

09:10.050 --> 09:11.968
and it was from that first time
that I knew it was gonna be

09:12.010 --> 09:13.928
something I wanted
to do long-term.

09:15.430 --> 09:18.308
<i>- So it was love</i>
<i>at first sight...</i>

09:18.350 --> 09:20.393
<i>even though,</i>
<i>like any good relationship,</i>

09:20.435 --> 09:23.688
<i>it took a lot of work for</i>
<i>Shuster to get to where he is</i>

09:23.730 --> 09:25.899
<i>at the top of the sport.</i>

09:25.940 --> 09:28.777
<i>From a bronze medal in 2006</i>

09:28.818 --> 09:33.156
<i>to dismal showings</i>
<i>in 2010 and 2014,</i>

09:33.198 --> 09:36.034
<i>and then finally gold</i>
<i>in PyeongChang.</i>

09:36.076 --> 09:38.912
<i>It's been a long</i>
<i>and winding road,</i>

09:38.953 --> 09:41.664
<i>all charted</i>
<i>in distinctive detail</i>

09:41.706 --> 09:43.958
<i>down in Shuster's basement.</i>

09:45.251 --> 09:46.628
- So like, that thing
I was telling you guys about

09:46.670 --> 09:48.254
is right here.

09:48.296 --> 09:50.090
We all had to make one of these
that were at this thing.

09:50.131 --> 09:51.299
There was, like, 100 of us,

09:51.341 --> 09:52.676
like, from a bunch
of different sports.

09:52.717 --> 09:55.387
And it was like how people,
like, leave fingerprints

09:55.428 --> 09:57.013
on whatever you're doing
kind of thing.

09:57.055 --> 09:58.640
And so we had
to draw this thing and--

09:58.682 --> 10:00.517
and yeah, and one of the things
I have on there was, like, a--

10:00.558 --> 10:04.312
a gold medal, and it's got
a turquoise colored ribbon,

10:04.354 --> 10:06.398
and a medal that has, like,
the exact same, like,

10:06.439 --> 10:08.191
markings as, like,
the PyeongChang medal,

10:08.233 --> 10:11.861
which blew my mind, like,
legitimately blew my mind.

10:11.903 --> 10:13.863
I drew that in 2005.

10:13.905 --> 10:15.490
"Everything happens
for a reason."

10:22.038 --> 10:23.331
All right, we're heading in.

10:24.749 --> 10:26.376
All right, buddy.
You got your mask?

10:26.418 --> 10:27.711
All right.

10:27.752 --> 10:30.046
<i>I think it would have</i>
<i>been probably, you know,</i>

10:30.088 --> 10:31.464
<i>easy to walk away</i>
<i>from the game,</i>

10:31.506 --> 10:33.717
<i>you know, after 2018.</i>

10:33.758 --> 10:35.343
<i>Kind of go out on top,</i>

10:35.385 --> 10:38.930
but I really love curling
and competing.

10:41.808 --> 10:43.226
Go.

10:46.688 --> 10:48.398
<i>My wife loves curling.</i>

10:48.440 --> 10:50.442
<i>I think she might like curling</i>
<i>more than I do.</i>

10:50.483 --> 10:52.861
- Mine are gonna fall out.

10:52.902 --> 10:54.362
- Mine were getting
really close.

10:54.404 --> 10:57.407
- I love watching curling,
and I love watching him curl.

10:59.451 --> 11:01.745
<i>There's no way else I'd like</i>
<i>to bring up my children</i>

11:01.786 --> 11:05.331
<i>than to let them see that</i>
<i>they can achieve their dreams</i>

11:05.373 --> 11:08.543
and that if they put everything
towards those goals

11:08.585 --> 11:11.421
and those dreams, that they can
do anything that they want.

11:11.463 --> 11:14.007
<i>- The fact that Sara</i>
<i>and my kids, you know,</i>

11:14.049 --> 11:16.176
<i>love, you know,</i>
<i>watching me compete as much</i>

11:16.217 --> 11:18.511
as I still love being
in the mix of competition,

11:18.553 --> 11:21.139
I think that's
a pretty good indicator

11:21.181 --> 11:23.224
that's it's something
I need to continue doing.

11:23.266 --> 11:26.061
- He's lucky, besides.
- I know.

11:38.114 --> 11:41.534
- Kick it.
'Cause I just gotta slice this.

11:43.995 --> 11:45.705
- Normally he's gone,
like, half the year,

11:45.747 --> 11:46.998
so I have to fend for myself,

11:47.040 --> 11:49.084
but with COVID,

11:49.125 --> 11:50.627
that was one perk,

11:50.669 --> 11:51.961
'cause he was home and bored,

11:52.003 --> 11:53.463
so he cooked all the time.

11:53.505 --> 11:56.591
- Yeah.
- Some pretty crazy stuff.

11:56.633 --> 11:58.051
I just do the baking.

11:58.093 --> 12:00.512
She's the baker.

12:01.513 --> 12:04.808
<i>- Matt Hamilton balances</i>
<i>the frozen ice in his life</i>

12:04.849 --> 12:06.559
<i>with a hot stove</i>

12:06.601 --> 12:09.813
<i>and quality time</i>
<i>with his wife Jen.</i>

12:09.854 --> 12:13.441
<i>The pair met through</i>
<i>a classically romantic,</i>

12:13.483 --> 12:16.444
<i>boy-meets-girl tale</i>
<i>they love to tell.</i>

12:16.486 --> 12:18.988
I met Jen in 2009.

12:19.030 --> 12:21.324
- We met...
- Over beer pong.

12:21.366 --> 12:24.577
- Playing beer pong
at a party downtown Madison.

12:24.619 --> 12:26.329
It was after a Badger game.

12:26.371 --> 12:29.290
- The deal was if he won that
I would come cheer for him.

12:29.332 --> 12:32.335
- Cheer on our team.
- So...

12:32.377 --> 12:36.214
- 12 years later--
- Still cheering on my team.

12:37.632 --> 12:39.592
This is the one.
You ready?

12:42.178 --> 12:43.096
- Ah!
- It was close.

12:43.138 --> 12:44.931
That was the distance.

12:44.973 --> 12:48.309
That was like that.

12:48.351 --> 12:51.938
<i>- It's a simple life,</i>
<i>and a far cry from the life</i>

12:51.980 --> 12:56.109
<i>of a viral star that he got</i>
