<i>No, he's an awesome dude.</i>

15:16.082 --> 15:18.293
He's, uh,
he's kind of like our...

15:18.335 --> 15:20.128
our team rock, so to speak.

15:20.170 --> 15:22.130
He's just so even-keeled.

15:24.966 --> 15:26.843
<i>- John Landsteiner is--</i>

15:26.885 --> 15:28.511
I don't know, he's just--
he's just a cool dude.

15:28.553 --> 15:31.139
You--you know exactly
what you're getting.

15:31.181 --> 15:32.724
- Golf is, like,
good for curling

15:32.766 --> 15:36.686
because it's like
a mentally challenging game.

15:36.728 --> 15:39.272
John Landsteiner is...

15:39.314 --> 15:41.483
I mean, he's my longest
teammate of my career.

15:41.524 --> 15:43.401
<i>You know, he's kind of the--</i>

15:43.443 --> 15:45.487
<i>the business manager</i>
<i>of the four of us,</i>

15:45.528 --> 15:47.572
<i>and then, you know,</i>
<i>when we go to the ice,</i>

15:47.614 --> 15:49.074
<i>he's kind of the business</i>
<i>manager there too.</i>

15:49.115 --> 15:52.577
<i>And he's doing all the little</i>
<i>things that, you know,</i>

15:52.619 --> 15:54.579
<i>help and allow us all</i>
<i>to do our jobs.</i>

15:54.621 --> 15:58.583
<i>- When John Shuster began</i>
<i>putting his band back together</i>

15:58.625 --> 16:00.960
<i>for another gold medal run,</i>

16:01.002 --> 16:04.297
<i>there were no guarantees</i>
<i>anyone else would return.</i>

16:04.339 --> 16:06.758
<i>But Landsteiner</i>
<i>didn't hesitate.</i>

16:06.800 --> 16:09.928
- The motivation for making
the run for Beijing

16:09.969 --> 16:12.514
is we had other work
that we wanted to do,

16:12.555 --> 16:17.185
<i>and that's hard to pass up</i>
<i>on the opportunity to do.</i>

16:18.478 --> 16:19.437
Oh, boy.

16:19.479 --> 16:21.815
Oh, boy.

16:26.945 --> 16:30.031
<i>- Remember,</i>
<i>Chris Plys is a rookie,</i>

16:30.073 --> 16:31.950
<i>the one member of the team</i>

16:31.991 --> 16:35.537
<i>who wasn't part of the gold</i>
<i>medal run in Pyeongchang.</i>

16:35.578 --> 16:38.623
<i>But that gives him something</i>
<i>the others don't have:</i>

16:38.665 --> 16:41.459
<i>a hunger to get</i>
<i>where they've been.</i>

16:41.501 --> 16:43.586
<i>- People in the U.S.</i>
<i>like to cheer for winners.</i>

16:43.628 --> 16:45.505
<i>I mean, you don't get</i>
<i>an opportunity</i>

16:45.547 --> 16:47.799
to join a defending Olympic
gold medal team

16:47.841 --> 16:49.592
very often, so...

16:49.634 --> 16:51.052
it just was an opportunity

16:51.094 --> 16:54.097
that doesn't come around
every day and couldn't pass up.

16:57.183 --> 16:59.269
<i>When I was younger,</i>

16:59.310 --> 17:01.312
I liked skateboarding
and snowboarding

17:01.354 --> 17:03.648
and doing all that kinda stuff.

17:03.690 --> 17:05.817
<i>I used to be angry person</i>
<i>on the ice.</i>

